WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.600
- I'm Laurence Hoff, I write Connected Pl

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:05.010
aces.

00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:08.400
It's a newsletter about the atmosphere, at Proto,

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:10.760
BlueSky, Fediverse, and the ecosystems, the

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:12.460
open social ecosystems.

00:00:12.460 --> 00:00:15.380
I'm very interested in like figuring out like what are these

00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:16.500
systems actually?

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:19.490
Like there's a lot of cool narratives about what these systems

00:00:19.490 --> 00:00:22.660
can create, but I want to understand what are they?

00:00:22.660 --> 00:00:27.600
And recently Paul Fugy wrote an interesting article, Pract

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:30.660
ical Decentralization, where he made two specific points

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:30.920
.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:33.410
The point of decentralization, he wrote, is to guarantee

00:00:33.410 --> 00:00:36.760
the rights of individuals and communities on the internet.

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:40.170
And secondly, he wrote, we use protocols to structure who

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:42.640
can do what.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:46.040
Protocol designs are often about the how, but the consequence of

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:48.180
the how is an authority model.

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:51.300
And I think that's super powerful because that really sells what

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:52.660
's actually at stake here.

00:00:52.660 --> 00:00:56.580
Like building protocols is cool, but what we're actually building

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:01.980
is authority models of like how social interaction happens on the internet

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:02.140
.

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:06.460
Like it's easy, like many people have been getting interested

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:09.320
in open protocols as a sort of response to big tech bad

00:01:09.320 --> 00:01:11.300
, and well, obviously big tech bad.

00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:14.880
But the reason big tech bad is because of the governance of

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:16.080
the big tech platforms.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:18.660
So that means very much like if we want to build different

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:22.140
platforms, new ecosystems, systems, this is very much about

00:01:22.460 --> 00:01:27.500
what sort of governance and authority models do these new ecosystems actually

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:29.260
allow.

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:31.880
And for that, I'm always very drawn to the statement

00:01:31.880 --> 00:01:34.930
by the cybernetician, Stafford Beer, with

00:01:34.930 --> 00:01:36.180
this great one liner.

00:01:36.180 --> 00:01:38.900
The purpose of a system is what it does.

00:01:38.900 --> 00:01:42.190
And I think that's both simple and powerful because it lets

00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:45.600
you cut through like all these normative statements and intentional language

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:47.810
about what you want to be happening.

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:50.720
But instead, you can look at what is the system,

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:52.240
what should be happening.

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:55.190
Like what, not what should be happening, sorry, but

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:57.160
what does it actually produce?

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:00.280
And for that, it's also worthwhile to look at a

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:01.900
little bit of the history of the internet.

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:06.000
Like internet runs on email, the internet runs on open protocols

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:08.450
, and the most famous one for emails is the SMTP

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:09.360
protocol.

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:14.000
And that protocol just said very little about purpose or governance or

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:14.800
anything at all.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:18.370
It just says the goal of this protocol is to transfer mail

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:20.290
reliably and efficiently.

00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:24.160
And it turns out we've been getting extremely good at transferring

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:26.160
email reliably and efficiently.

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:31.380
And it also turns out that spam loves to be transferred reliably

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:32.800
and efficiently.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:35.730
So once you build an open protocol and like you have this

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:38.290
statement of like, hey, we want to do this thing

00:02:38.290 --> 00:02:38.520
.

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:41.440
And then otherwise, like you have a technical statement, but

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:44.380
you don't say anything about the governance or the power that

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:46.360
you create with this new system.

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:50.270
You can have a decentralized open protocol all you want, but

00:02:50.270 --> 00:02:54.760
these gaps for power, they get filled by economic models.

00:02:54.760 --> 00:02:57.520
And that's exactly what we have seen with email.

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:00.720
Like spam filtering turns out to be a huge problem.

00:03:00.760 --> 00:03:02.540
Google got very good at that.

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:06.350
And now email is basically duopoly with Google and Microsoft.

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:11.480
So open protocols, still duopoly, still centralized power because

00:03:11.480 --> 00:03:15.880
the protocol itself did not account for how it generates power.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:20.470
In general, that means power and value accumulates in the

00:03:20.470 --> 00:03:22.920
layer of a protocol that doesn't govern.

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:24.940
We've seen the same with HTTP.

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:28.440
Like HTTP also, the spec of the protocol has like,

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:30.470
says nothing about power.

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:33.690
Like Tim Berners-Lee made lots of blog posts around

00:03:34.040 --> 00:03:36.930
it about like great ideas of what you want the power to

00:03:36.930 --> 00:03:37.300
be.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:41.580
But because that wasn't defined in the spec anywhere, then

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:46.790
that allowed that value and the power to be accumulated in the

00:03:46.850 --> 00:03:47.710
layers around it.

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:49.880
And that's how we got in this system of like,

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:54.710
well, big tech bad, because these companies could accumulate this

00:03:54.760 --> 00:03:57.400
power in the layers around HTTPS.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:02.320
And we've seen like, we've been doing open protocols

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:04.970
for a long time, like since the early '80s

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:05.240
.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:09.440
And now we've seen that in the last decade or so

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:11.080
, we've seen new protocols arise.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:12.710
We've seen ActivityPub, we've seen N

00:04:12.710 --> 00:04:14.890
ostra, we've seen Matrix and now at Proto

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:15.580
as well.

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:19.160
And these protocols start to incorporate normative language in the protocol

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:20.270
documentation.

00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:22.160
They say stuff about governance.

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:26.470
They say stuff about what should this be doing, what should

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:27.840
this system create?

00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:32.150
And I got three quotes from the Proto documentation here.

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:34.710
And I do think it's very interesting to see the norm

00:04:34.860 --> 00:04:36.090
ative statements pop up here.

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:38.660
Speech and reads should be two separate layers.

00:04:38.660 --> 00:04:41.590
Also the very normative, everybody should have, everybody has

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:41.980
a voice.

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:45.120
And users are free to select their aggregators.

00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:50.620
The protocol design sort of tradition sort of assumes a sequence.

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:54.930
First, you build an architecture, the design specification.

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:59.290
Then you grow an ecosystem, and then you add governance to

00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:00.550
that ecosystem.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:04.320
But, it turns out, like, growing that ecosystem is

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:07.360
the same as adding governance to this ecosystem.

00:05:07.360 --> 00:05:13.050
Because, like, if you do not actually specifically specify,

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:16.110
like, the governance of the ecosystem, once you grow it

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:22.080
, like, the implicit forms of governance, which are often

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:24.760
, like, if it's not specified, it's just

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:28.090
the most powerful economic actor who is there first, turns out

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:30.200
to be, become the governance layer.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:33.270
And the reason for that is that because if you grow an

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:37.020
ecosystem or open protocol, you create shared resources.

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:42.840
And these shared resources are themselves governance structures because they compete,

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:44.660
they involve competing interest.

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:47.340
For example, here on Proto, like, if you

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:50.100
build, if you run a relay, you immediately need to

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:51.440
make governance decisions.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:53.890
You need to decide, am I going to -- which spam

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:55.250
am I going to filter out?

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:57.360
Am I going to filter the abuse out?

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:59.360
Am I going to filter copyright material out?

00:05:59.360 --> 00:06:02.170
Or am I going to transfer these -- like, am I

00:06:02.170 --> 00:06:06.180
just going to say I'm a neutral -- neutral -- layer

00:06:06.460 --> 00:06:08.270
that just transfers all of this?

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:12.670
And, like, there is not a neutral way to transfer

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:17.270
spam or a neutral way to transfer abuse in your relay.

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:21.150
As soon as you operate a relay, you have made governance

00:06:21.150 --> 00:06:24.170
decisions because these are the shared resources.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:28.870
like, there's an article I wrote recently about the purpose

00:06:28.870 --> 00:06:30.200
of protocols.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:33.410
And I got two responses from Paul on that, that I

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:36.170
think both are worth highlighting.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:38.240
First, he said, like, my belief and hope is

00:06:38.430 --> 00:06:41.200
that we've opened the opportunities for other forms of communal resource

00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:42.200
governance to be implemented.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:45.120
And, like, I very strongly agree with that.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:48.090
Like, this is why I care about these open ecosystems.

00:06:48.120 --> 00:06:50.760
And this is why I care about, like, this conference

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:53.790
because, like, there's so many people around here that

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:56.120
, like, that can -- we can build these systems now

00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:56.120
.

00:06:56.120 --> 00:07:01.220
We have created this infrastructure, we can create this communal resource

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:04.850
government, like, we have this open -- open relays

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:08.040
, we can build the governance structures for it.

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:10.730
But Paul also says, I'm almost ready to say that

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:14.020
the economics are determinative of the governance.

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:17.710
Well, I am actually ready to say that the economics are

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:21.260
determinative, but if they are determinative, what do

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:21.950
they actually determine?

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:29.190
For that, let's look a little bit more in detail

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:31.560
on what AppProto actually does.

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:34.490
And, basically, it creates two layers, a speech layer

00:07:34.490 --> 00:07:36.550
, a speech is just, like, it's cheap,

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:39.240
it's permissive, everybody can publish, it's

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:41.040
very easy to set up your own PDS.

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:43.040
And then there's the reach layer.

00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:44.890
The reach is, like, that's where you get the

00:07:44.890 --> 00:07:47.240
feed algorithms, that's where you get the app views,

00:07:47.270 --> 00:07:49.530
that's where you get the indexes, that's where

00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:51.950
the people actually interact with your app.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:55.060
And the reach layer, that's actually the expensive part of

00:07:55.060 --> 00:07:58.860
operating infrastructure, and thus, that's where the economics are

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:00.400
actually determinative.

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:03.160
And that's actually what you now see in the atmosphere in

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:05.580
practice, like, Blue Sky, the company, is,

00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:08.840
like, three orders of magnitude larger than any of the other

00:08:08.950 --> 00:08:13.780
operators, because the economics are determinative, and they operate

00:08:13.780 --> 00:08:16.310
the expensive layers of the stack.

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.720
I want to zoom in even more, I'm going to

00:08:18.950 --> 00:08:22.420
specifically zoom in on, like, the algorithmic choice here

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:22.680
.

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:25.410
We do, like, AppProto allows for algorithmic

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:28.950
choice, allows for everybody to run their own feed operators,

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:29.620
et cetera.

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:35.020
But feed providers need users, users want engaging content, and

00:08:35.020 --> 00:08:39.080
the thing is, what counts as engaging content is what everybody

00:08:39.090 --> 00:08:40.760
else is engaging with.

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:46.250
Like, our preferences for what we want to see, what

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:51.510
we think is engaging is not neutral, it's not defined

00:08:51.580 --> 00:08:54.860
by the individual, it's defined by the people around us

00:08:54.920 --> 00:08:55.200
.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:59.010
Because we are, like, our preferences are shaped by other

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:03.720
preferences, and our preferences are intrinsically mimetic.

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:05.880
And for that, I want to zoom in on the for

00:09:05.970 --> 00:09:09.000
you feed by the independent developer SpaceCowboy.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.900
SpaceCowboy, it's an amazing feed, and

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:15.820
it has actually a fairly straightforward mechanism.

00:09:16.040 --> 00:09:18.910
It looks at the post you liked, like, then it

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:22.800
looks at what other people also liked that post, and what

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:26.430
other POs they like, and they suggest then that post

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:27.030
to you.

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:30.110
There's even, like, this very explicit sense of,

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:32.710
like, how we made it visible of, like, how

00:09:32.710 --> 00:09:35.940
our preferences mimic other people's preferences.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:40.090
That is exactly, in its most pure form, what the

00:09:40.150 --> 00:09:42.000
for you feed does.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.430
And actually, if you spend any time here in the ecosystem

00:09:44.530 --> 00:09:47.180
, the AppRoto developer ecosystem, you know that people

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:49.240
actually really like the for you feed.

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:51.930
It is a very great feed, and people recommend it all

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:52.450
the time.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:55.840
It's almost kind of a meme, especially if you compare

00:09:56.150 --> 00:10:00.220
it to the other popular algorithmic feed, the Discover feed

00:10:00.220 --> 00:10:02.000
by Blue Sky itself.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.550
And that's also a bit of a meme to almost hate

00:10:04.590 --> 00:10:06.680
on, like, the Discover feed.

00:10:06.680 --> 00:10:08.400
Shout out to Dan for that.

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:14.130
Like, the reason for that is that, sorry, what

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:17.310
's actually interesting about the Discover feed, Blue Sky's Discover

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:19.880
feed, is that it's an algorithmic feed, but

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:22.400
it's not purely engagement based.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:26.210
Because Blue Sky's also trying to solve for other problems than

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:29.000
just pure engagement recommendation.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.610
They also solve for a problem of, hey, there's

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:34.680
a new person signing up.

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:37.740
We don't know anything about that new person, but we

00:10:37.740 --> 00:10:40.080
don't want to show them an empty feed.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:43.890
So how are we going to show them some interesting content via

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:45.560
the Discover feed?

00:10:45.560 --> 00:10:47.280
And the Discover feed is very good at that.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:51.050
It has multiple purposes, and it's good at those purposes

00:10:51.050 --> 00:10:51.360
.

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:53.800
But what it reveals, and what you can see in how

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:56.940
the AdPro, the developer community engages with both feeds,

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:03.070
is that the reveal preference is that people strongly prefer pure engagement

00:11:03.070 --> 00:11:08.740
-driven feeds over generically algorithmic feeds that also provide

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:09.960
other features.

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:12.560
So now we start to see.

00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:15.770
So now we start to see that there becomes a loop.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.240
And users engage with what other people engage with.

00:11:20.240 --> 00:11:24.060
And what a prototype does, it creates this single shared data

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:25.000
space.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:29.020
Like, this is the nature of this open protocol that everybody

00:11:29.020 --> 00:11:31.580
has, like, and the relays, all the rel

00:11:31.580 --> 00:11:33.900
ays, all the app views connect to all that single data

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.120
, that data space.

00:11:35.120 --> 00:11:38.320
Like, this means there's this singular shared data space.

00:11:38.360 --> 00:11:42.490
So users engage with what other people engage with, and that

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:45.560
gets captured by that shared data space.

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:47.660
Like, that gets captured by the likes on the lexic

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:49.040
ons, et cetera, et cetera.

00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:54.000
And these feed providers then look at this entire data space,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:59.240
pick out the most engaging content from that data space, because

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:02.620
that's what the feed providers want, because that's what

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:03.300
the users want.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:05.830
And then you see, again, get back to the top

00:12:05.870 --> 00:12:08.980
, users engage with what other people's most engaged with.

00:12:08.980 --> 00:12:14.770
So here we get this very interesting dynamic, what it means

00:12:14.770 --> 00:12:18.460
that if you have algorithmic choice in a single shared data

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:21.540
space, that produces convergence.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:25.500
And that means, like, you have, what I mean

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:28.720
with that is that because of this loop, we get,

00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:32.860
like, we converge on this single centralizing point of the

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:34.840
most engaging content.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:37.700
And, like, this doesn't mean there's room for

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:40.380
, like, niche content and niche feeds.

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:43.590
You can still always create the Moz feed all you want,

00:12:43.860 --> 00:12:46.100
but this is, by definition, niche.

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:48.500
And there's, like, what you get is, like

00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:51.180
, this main set of feed that are, like, highly

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:54.980
engagement-driven because the underlying data space is, like,

00:12:54.980 --> 00:12:58.360
reflects this engagement-driven optimization.

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:01.250
And you have a very long tail of a whole lot of

00:13:01.250 --> 00:13:03.720
niches of algorithmic choices.

00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:07.470
You can actually already see this in Blue Sky's culture where

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:09.560
, like, all the data is open.

00:13:09.560 --> 00:13:12.520
You can look at what content is the most liked on any

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:16.060
day, and that consistently converges on American left-li

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:17.380
beral politics.

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:22.350
And that's exactly what we would expect in this virtuous feedback

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:27.040
loop of, like, that this diversity of feed providers select

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:29.820
s for the most engaging content.

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:33.470
So the open system is competing on engagement, and that's

00:13:33.480 --> 00:13:35.260
how you get convergence.

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:39.650
So you have an architecture that says pluralism, but the

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:43.920
economics of it says, no, you actually have convergence.

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:47.950
So we have a protocol, like the protocols, that focuses

00:13:47.950 --> 00:13:53.400
very much on individual rights, but these rights only matter as

